  "diary": "Woke up to check on my sourdough starter—it's been looking good this week. The rain started early, so I grabbed my usual breakfast sandwich at Blazer Bagels and tried to enjoy it before heading to the site. All day was basically me trudging around in the drizzle, coordinating with contractors and reviewing budgets. The SR-520 closure had everyone stressed about logistics, but thankfully it didn't directly impact our U-District work. Grabbed lunch from the food truck—same spot, same order. By afternoon my boots were soaked through, but the inspections had to happen. Stopped at the market on the way home to pick up flour; there's something grounding about that ritual. Spent the evening shaping loaves for overnight fermentation and jotting down birdwatching notes from the week. Felt good to end the day with something tangible I'd made with my hands.",
  "thought_process": "The rain set the tone early—everything felt heavier, slower. I stayed close to routine because the weather made deviations feel pointless. Work was steady but unremarkable; the SR-520 closure was a headache I watched others deal with, grateful our site wasn't affected. I think I leaned into the domestic stuff tonight—baking, notes on birds—because the day was all logistics and problem-solving. There's a balance I need between the job and home, and rainy days make me crave the latter. The sourdough starter and birdwatching feel like they're anchoring me lately.",
